The battle between AfriForum and the EFF continues on Monday in the high court in Johannesburg. AfriForum's deputy CEO, Ernst Roets further accuses EFF leaders Julius Malema and Mbuyiseni Ndlozi of acting against the Constitution. Roets spoke with eNCA's Gareth Edwards about the court case. Courtesy of #DStv403  JOHANNESBURG - AfriForum wants the EFF and its leaders to apologise publicly and pay for damages. That’s for singing the anti-apartheid song "Dubul' ibhunu", which translates to "shoot the boer", on various occasions. READ: SAHRC: Malema comments not hate speech AfriForum is bringing a civil case against the EFF in court on Monday. "This is a civil matter, hate speech is not a crime in SA, it is something that you can sue and claim damage," said AfriForum's Ernst Roets. "So what we are saying is a public apology, but also that the court can declare that this is indeed hate speech."